<br>
Agree with you 100% on the Walmart-effect:  shop big-box, sell-out your community.  However with annual sales over $160 billion and millions of spandex and XXXXL t-shirt wearing bovinesc shoppers praising Walmart for &quot;looking out for them&quot;, I'm sure you can still see my arguement.<br>
<br>
As for Iran-Contra:  if you think that is the most immoral operation that the US has undertaken and executed, then think again.  Furthermore, if the Iran side of the operation had worked out as planned, I think the tune would have been a bit different...same with Korea...and Vietnam...  <br>
<br>
Oliver North is just an example of the duality that exists within public perception.  Look at Bill Clinton:  busted for getting gummers in the Oval Office by a barely-legal White House aide, he used every Slick-Willy trick in the book to evade prosecution and impeachment (successfully mind you), and after all is said and done, his approval rating went up?  What about he and Hillary's involvement in White Water and the Rose law firm?  How many people surrounding that fiasco died of mysterious circumstances?  But things appeared to be just fine and dandy during Clinton's administration so folks are willing to turn a semi-blind eye to everything.<br>
<br>
My point is this:  morality has very little meaning anymore and there are no moral heroes.  Self-interest and personal security override the public's overall perception of decision makers and the governing body.  If interest rates are high, unemployment is high, domestic growth is low, and the US is out there, conducting immoral operations - then folks bitch and drop their jaws in suprise and disgust.  <br>
<br>
However when economic growth is rampant, millionaires are being made overnight on bullsh*t business plans, McDonald's is cheap, and folks can laugh at Seinfeld every night, who really cares if men and women in US military garb, or behind computer screens in intelligence think tanks are killing babies or plotting political insurrections elsewhere in the world - pass me another Coors light and a bag of Doritos...it's Sunday Night Football!<br>
